body.p: The RCP (Ring Control Port) interface has two separate RCPs:

The receive and transmit RI_RCP carries BDI/BEI/BIAE bits from the sink framers and the APS/PCC bytes. The DI_DCP transmits defects and alarms. RI_RCP is standard XFI running at 10.3125 Gbps and DI_RCP is standard SGMIIs (Serial Gigabit Media Independent Interfaces) running at 1.25 Gbps. See ODU Ring Control Port Block (ODU_RCP)
SERDES P/N signals can be swapped on a per lane basis. Independent configuration for P/N swap in the Tx and Rx direction is supported.
The frame format is described in ODU Ring Control Port Block (ODU_RCP) for both RI_RCP and DI_RCP.
The signals use M10 family SERDES from the Multimode SERDES at 10Gbps cell set. For details, see 1. Note also that the M10 SERDES are synchronous to the PCIE_REFCLK reference clock.

Note that the M10 SERDES does not provide the register configurability to swap the polarity of the Transmit P/N data and Receive P/N data signals. The Tx PCS for this interface does not have the ability to change the polarity of P/N, however the Rx PCS does have the capability to swap the polarity of P/N.

pmc-description.p: - Added "Table 22 Reference and Power Filtering Pin Description" to the pin description section. Refer to the hardware design guide for components and connections required for the power filtering pins.
- Internal Updated "Table 84 Normal Operating Voltages" with complete list of pins for the AVD_0V8, AVD_1V8, and VDDO_1V8 power domains.
- Added bootstrap option pins BEN, BST[1:0], CBT[2:0], MSE, MSM, MSR, NEN to "Table 3 DIGI-G5 Device Interface Pin Description".
- Changed software API names to reflect development 1.0.0 release of the DIGI-G5 Device Family Software Development Kit (SDK).
- Added test point receive and transmit pins to "Table 3 DIGI-G5 Device Interface Pin Description".

- Added "Table 22 Reference and Power Filtering Pin Description" to the pin description section. Refer to the hardware design guide for components and connections required for the power filtering pins.
- Internal Updated "Table 84 Normal Operating Voltages" with complete list of pins for the AVD_0V8, AVD_1V8, and VDDO_1V8 power domains.
- Added bootstrap option pins BEN, BST[1:0], CBT[2:0], MSE, MSM, MSR, NEN to "Table 3 DIGI-G5 Device Interface Pin Description".
- Changed software API names to reflect development 1.0.0 release of the DIGI-G5 Device Family Software Development Kit (SDK).
- Added test point receive and transmit pins to "Table 3 DIGI-G5 Device Interface Pin Description".
- Increased number of SERDES on Bank C from 20 to 24.
- Indicated lane order reversal of SERDES Bank A on Device PCB Floor Planning Diagram.
- Added ODUjk mux 100G Capacity Resource tables for 600G and 500G modes of operation.
- Updated text and diagrams to show support for 24x10GE.
- Removed references to PM6012 and PM6013.
- Removed support for SSPRQ, JP03A and JP03B SerDes patterns to align with standards.

body.p: The Non-Transparent Endpoint (NT EP) offers access to Switchtec's Non-Transparent Bridge (NTB) through mapping windows in the NT EP's Memory Space. It is presented to the RC as function 0 of the upstream port when the USP port mode is NT EP only, or as function 1 in the upstream port when the USP port mode supports transparent switching, as well. The following sections outline the details of the non-transparent endpoint.

topic.title: FlashPowerCreditUpdate

body.p: This message is sent to update flash power credit for different commands. The current power credits are allocated based on the maximum power required for a particular command, in future this can be broken down to smaller granular if needed based on the flash state.

description.p: This field encodes the request message type. The value of this field is microcode specific.
This field encodes the Flash channel queue associated with this message request.
This field encodes the Flash channel associated with this message request.
This field contains the node address of the next request message in the message chain. A value of zero in this field indicates that this is the last message of a message chain.

When this bit is set, the request message is part of a chained message and is not the last message in the message chain. The address of the next request message in the message chain is specified by the chMsgNodeAddr field.
This field specifies the index of Flash completion outbound message queue to be used by this message.
This field contains opaque data that is passed from the request to the corresponding completion.
This field encodes the request sub message type. The value of this field is microcode specific.
This field specifies the Power units for the Read command, which includes the flash array read power and I/O burst read power.
This field specifies the Power units for the Program command, which includes the flash array program power and I/O burst read power.
This field specifies the Power units for the Erase command.
This specifies the maximum power used by any other commands like Read Status, Set feature, Get feature, etc

topic.title: FlashDynamicUpdate

body.p: This message is sent to update flash parameters that can be changed at run time.

description.p: This field encodes the request message type. The value of this field is microcode specific.
This field encodes the Flash channel queue associated with this message request.
This field encodes the Flash channel associated with this message request.
This field contains the node address of the next request message in the message chain. A value of zero in this field indicates that this is the last message of a message chain.

When this bit is set, the request message is part of a chained message and is not the last message in the message chain. The address of the next request message in the message chain is specified by the chMsgNodeAddr field.
This field specifies the index of Flash completion outbound message queue to be used by this message.
This field contains opaque data that is passed from the request to the corresponding completion.
This field encodes the request sub message type. The value of this field is microcode specific.
This field specifies the poll limit for the high priority message processing.
